  <hyper:location>
    <hyper:title>Our Mission</hyper:title>
    <hyper:description xlabel="here">
      <h:section>
        <h:p><h:a href="hyperspace.xml">Hyperspaces</h:a> are <h:strong>not</h:strong> a new idea.</h:p>
        
        <h:p>The <h:a href="https://www.w3.org/History/1989/proposal.html">original vision of the web</h:a> recognized the fundamental challenge of  navigating a large, complex, constantly-evolving <h:a href="http://wiki.c2.com/?ProblemDomain">problem space</h:a> and it suggested a remarkable solution: <h:em>map the solution space</h:em>.</h:p>
        
        <h:p>Literally.</h:p>
        
        <h:p>A <h:strong>web</h:strong> of "notes" <h:strong>linked</h:strong> to other notes where each note, or node, would have a different <h:em>type</h:em> and might represent <h:em>anything</h:em> from a person to an abstract concept, collaboratively edited, constantly evolving in real-time as new information was discovered and new knowledge integrated, would, over time, better facilitate communication and collaboration than any kind of rigid hierarchical information system or overly structured documentation.</h:p>
        
        <h:p>This 30 year-old vision that inspired the world-wide web was certainly on to something. Thus <h:a href="hyperspace.xml">hyperspaces</h:a>.</h:p>
        
        <h:p>But if hyperspaces are just the web and they're certainly not anything new then why <h:a href="https://explorable.com/definition-of-research">research</h:a> them?</h:p>
        
        <h:p>Well, we think there's still <h:strong>a lot to learn</h:strong> about hyperspaces.</h:p>
        
        <h:p>The web has flourished over the past thirty years but for all it has accomplished we're still just scratching the surface of the true potential.</h:p>
        
        <h:p>We suspect that hyperspaces can and should be used to <h:strong>solve real, complex, ever-evolving problems</h:strong> and that when used correctly they can <h:strong>dramatically transform an organization</h:strong> as its members become more effective at communicating and collaborating with one another.</h:p>
        
        <h:p>Our mission then is to show how this might be done. To show that a hyperspace can be a powerful instrument of change we should like to <h:a href="http://www.quote-wise.com/quotes/mahatma-gandhi/if-we-could-change-ourselves-the-tendencies-i">be the change</h:a>.</h:p>

        <h:p>We think this adventure is going to be lots of fun. If you like feel free to come along for the ride!</h:p>
      </h:section>  
